    </nav> 
    <section id="assignment" class="container assignment"> 
     <figure>
      <img src="http://www.drew.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/106/classics-graphic.gif">
      <figcaption>
       <strong>Most university departments have names that come from Greek or Latin because that’s when the disciplines began</strong>
       <br> 
       <strong>Economics </strong>Gr. oikonomia=household management
       <br> 
       <strong>Politics </strong>Gr. ta politika=matters of state
       <br> 
       <strong>Zoology</strong> Gr. zoion=animal, logia=speaking, study of
      </figcaption>
     </figure> 
    </section> 
    <section id="careers" class="careers"> 
     <section class="container"> 
      <h2>Careers Made easy</h2> 
      <h3>Press Rewind</h3> 
      <p>Classics might seem specialized, but since it’s the foundation of all liberal education it’s as broad as it can be. Many students find it a <strong>natural fit for a double major</strong>, pairing classics with philosophy, art history, English, religion, theatre arts, even biology.</p> 
      <p>Grad schools and employers <strong>appreciate this education</strong>. Go to law school or pursue disciplines such as political science, civil engineering or theater, all founded on classical ideas.</p> 
      <p>We take regular trips to the Metropolitan Museum in New York to see its <strong>amazing collection of antiquities</strong>. If that’s not adequate, intern there. It’s been done, and we can help.<br> </p>
     </section> 
    </section> 
    <section id="thepeople" class="thepeople"> 
     <div class="rightslider">
      <div id="carousel-student" class="touchcarousel drew resize ">
       <ul class="touchcarousel-container"> 
        <div> 
         <li class="touchcarousel-item"><img width="683" height="460" src="http://www.drew.edu/undergraduate/wp-content/uploads/sites/106/costikyan1.jpg" class="attachment-thepeople wp-post-image" alt="costikyan"> <h2 class="type">Full-Impact Students</h2> <h2 class="name">Betsy Costikyan</h2> <p>Classics education has always been very important to universities both abroad and in the United States. It’s nice keeping that tradition alive. It’s also expanded my interests to a more worldly place. Learning languages absolutely opens up a whole new way to experience things.</p> </li> 
         <li class="touchcarousel-item"><img width="683" height="460" src="http://www.drew.edu/undergraduate/wp-content/uploads/sites/106/mattera1.jpg" class="attachment-thepeople wp-post-image" alt="mattera"> <h2 class="type">Full-Impact Students</h2> <h2 class="name">Caitlin Mattera</h2> <p>While I was explaining some myths to my friends, it hit me that stories—like those of Hector and Perseus—are extremely important to me. I want to be a writer and I realized that the classics are too important a component of literature and of my own story and interests for me to ignore.</p> </li> 
        </div> 
       </ul>
      </div>
     </div> 
     <div class="leftslider">
      <div id="carousel-faculty" class="touchcarousel drew resize ">
       <ul class="touchcarousel-container"> 
        <div> 
         <li class="touchcarousel-item"><img width="683" height="460" src="http://www.drew.edu/undergraduate/wp-content/uploads/sites/106/lenz1.jpg" class="attachment-thepeople wp-post-image" alt="lenz"> <h2 class="type">Passionate Faculty</h2> <h2 class="name">John R. Lenz</h2> <h2>Associate professor &amp; chair</h2> <p>I once had a student tell me that he went to a job interview and got the job because they talked about the Greek historian Thucydides the whole time. As for me, I’m researching ancient Greek religion and how it differed from, and evolved into, Christianity.</p> <p><strong>Ph.D., Columbia University</strong></p> </li> 
         <li class="touchcarousel-item"><img width="683" height="460" src="http://www.drew.edu/undergraduate/wp-content/uploads/sites/106/mucciogrosso1.jpg" class="attachment-thepeople wp-post-image" alt="mucciogrosso"> <h2 class="type">Passionate Faculty</h2> <h2 class="name">John D. Muccigrosso</h2> <h2>Associate professor</h2> <p>I run the <em>Vicus ad Martis Tudertium </em>Project, an archaeological excavation in Umbria that’s open as a field school to students. I take a special interest in Italian archaeology. In Italy more than anywhere else, you’re much more likely to hit something if you put a hole in the ground.</p> <p><strong>Ph.D., University of Michigan</strong></p> </li> 
        </div>
       </ul>
      </div>
     </div> 
